U.S. Stocks Fall Amid Concern U.S. Economy Is Faltering

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-08-10T13:31:03Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-10/u-s-stocks-fall-s-p-500-index-loses-1-4-.html
U.S. stocks fell at the start of
trading, as measured by the Standard & Poor's 500 Index, at 9:31
a.m. New York time.  The  S&P 500  dropped 1.4 percent to 1,156.63. There were 3
stocks that rose and 243 that fell. Microsoft Corp., down 3
percent to $24.81, led the decline. The  Dow Jones Industrial
Average  fell 1.3 percent to 11,097.79. For the year, the S&P 500
has lost 8 percent. The Dow has dropped 4.1 percent.   Bank of America Corp. was the most-active U.S. stock.
Trading totaled 19.6 million shares. Other actively traded shares
included Sirius XM Radio Inc., Ford Motor Co., General Electric
Co., and Advanced Micro Devices Inc..  Microsoft Corp. dragged the S&P 500's value down by 0.63
point, more than any other stock, followed by Apple Inc. at 0.49
point and JPMorgan Chase & Co. at 0.49 point. Pfizer Inc. limited
the indexâ€™s loss the most, lifting its value by 0.10 point,
followed by Capital One Financial Corp. at 0.02 point and Newmont
Mining Corp. at 0.01 point.   S&P 500 futures expiring in September fell 26.70 points to
1,145.00, a discount of 8.81 points to the index's fair value.
The futures are fairly valued at a discount of 2.82 to the
underlying cash index, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  The Stoxx Europe 600 Index fell 1.1 percent to 229.60. The
Euro Stoxx 50 Index, a measure of shares in nations using the
common currency, retreated 1.1 percent to 2,237.76. The MSCI Asia
Pacific Index climbed 2.2 percent to 123.08.  Yields on 10-year U.S. Treasury notes fell to 2.16 percent
from 2.25 percent. The Dollar Index, which measures the U.S.
currency against the euro, yen, pound, Canadian dollar, Swedish
krona and Swiss franc, rose 0.7 percent to 74.440.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Baker at   nbaker7@bloomberg.net . 